"CORE_NARRATIVE: Traditional light field depth estimation fails in complex scenes because relying solely on **spatial textures or EPI slopes** cannot **decouple Lambertian from non-Lambertian reflections**. By introducing **MRI-like k-space frequency domain analysis** and a **dual-mask mechanism**, we map reflection types to **angular spectra**, achieving precise **pixel-level physical material representation** and overcoming **spatial-domain limitations** for robust depth estimation.\n\nINTRO_HOOK: Open by highlighting the catastrophic depth failures in **complex, real-world mixed scenes**, explicitly blaming the traditional reliance on **spatial textures or EPI slopes** for their inability to **decouple Lambertian from non-Lambertian reflections**.\n\nGAP_BRIDGE: Transition by arguing that current methods fail because they ignore the physical optics of **light-matter interactions**, necessitating a shift toward **angular frequency physical representation** to overcome inherent **spatial-domain limitations**.\n\nMETHOD_JUSTIFY: Justify the design by explaining that applying **MRI-like k-space frequency domain analysis** to the angular matrix physically maps reflection types to frequency bands, while the **dual-mask mechanism** and **inverse wavevector analysis** ensure **lightweight BRDF parameter estimation** strictly obeys physical optics.\n\nEXPERIMENT_VALIDATE: Validate the motivation by demonstrating that extracting **angular spectra** achieves high material classification accuracy and **lightweight BRDF parameter estimation** without massive neural networks, ultimately proving that physical decoupling yields superior depth maps and precise **pixel-level physical material representation**.\n\nCONCLUSION_ECHO: Echo the motivation by reiterating that leveraging **angular frequency analysis** and **dual-masking** **overcomes spatial-domain limitations**, thereby fundamentally solving the non-Lambertian bottleneck and enhancing the **robustness and applicability of light field technologies**."